patient care, the more error we find. No setting is free from hazards; no specialty is immune; and patients are at risk no matter what their age, sex, or health status. But the risk is not homogeneous. Patients who are sicker, subjected to multiple interventions, and remain in hospital longer are more likely to suffer serious injury as a result of medical mistakes. Unless we make substantial changes in the organization and delivery of health care, all patients—particularly the most vulnerable—will continue to bear the burden of medical error.
